        "headline": "The Harlem Gateway Waterfront: Local community responds to impending redevelopment of 125th St. West Harlem Piers",
        "date": "February 22, 2023",
        "byline": "By Manuela Silva, Erica Lee, and Isha Banerjee",
        "pages": {
          "Page_0_link": "",
          "Page_0_title": "New Harlem Rocket Tours scheduled to come to 125th St. Piers in summer of 2023",
          "page_0_cover_img": "https://cloudfront-us-east-1.images.arcpublishing.com/spectator/XE2POW5ACZHOHPJDMWHXI2T43Y.jpg",
          "page_0_cover_caption": "Grace Li / Staff Photographer",
          "page_0_heading": "Part 1: Rocket Tours",
          "page_0_date": "February 22, 2023",
          "page_0_byline": "By <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/contributors/Manuela-Silva/\">Manuela Silva</a>",
          "page_1_link": "",
          "page_1_title": "135th Street Marine Transfer Station proposed to be converted into a Harlem Maritime Technology Center and Museum",
          "page_1_cover_img": "https://cloudfront-us-east-1.images.arcpublishing.com/spectator/25OCFU5XD5EMRFXY32FOKNWDBQ.jpg",
          "page_1_cover_caption": "Grace Li / Staff Photographer",
          "page_1_heading": "Part 2: Maritime Museum",
          "page_1_date": "February 22, 2023",
          "page_1_byline": "By <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/contributors/Erica-Lee/\">Erica Lee</a>",
          "page_2_link": "",
          "page_2_title": "180-foot tall ferris wheel proposed to boost tourism of West Harlem Piers Park",
          "Page_2_cover_img": "https://cloudfront-us-east-1.images.arcpublishing.com/spectator/DKOBI7YZXVHC3ISIFZSJV4VNWU.jpg",
          "page_2_cover_caption": "Grace Li / Staff Photographer",
          "page_2_heading": "Part 3: Ferris Wheel",
          "page_2_date": "February 22, 2023",
          "page_2_byline": "By <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/contributors/Isha-Banerjee/\">Isha Banerjee</a>"
        },
        "bodies": {
          "page_0": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Starting in July of 2023, New Yorkers and tourists alike will be able to take a high-speed boat tour of the Hudson River along the Harlem and Upper Manhattan waterfront. The inauguration of the new boat tours, which will launch from the West Harlem Piers, marks the beginning of a project that had been originally scheduled for before the pandemic."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The new Harlem Rocket Tour is the first of three new attractions planned for the 125th St. West Harlem Piers as part of the Harlem Gateway Waterfront Initiative. The initiative, led by Paradise Express Ferry, is New York City’s only Black-owned maritime enterprise. For now, the Harlem Rocket Tours is the only approved part of the three-part plan. The other two parts—a ferris wheel and a museum centered on Harlem’s maritime history—are still in conceptual stages."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The boat tours are set to cast off from a dock currently occupied by the Baylander Steel Beach restaurant. Both the Baylander restaurant and the Harlem Rocket Tours will lease the usage of the pier from the city, which currently owns it."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The tours, which will operate on a 93-passenger high-speed boat, will run along the Harlem and Upper Manhattan waterfront multiple times throughout the day. The Harlem Rocket Tours website also mentions that the tours will be “integrated with novel drone, AI, and cloud-storage technologies.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Michael Trenk, the owner of the Baylander, said he welcomes the new attractions."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“I always have a saying: business permeates business,” Trenk said. “More people would go by my boat after they go on the Harlem Rocket, might want a refreshing drink after they’ve been on the Hudson.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Garry Johnson, the CEO of Paradise Express Ferry, noted that he had been in contact with other local businesses, including the owner of the famed Dinosaur Bar-B-Que, regarding the new tours. He said he was excited about the increased business the tours will bring. For Johnson, the new attractions are a way to “level the playing field.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“We view this in the lens of economic development as a complement to some of the other efforts that have gone on, and particularly in light of waterfront economic development,” Johnson said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Johnson noted that ferry operations similar to the Harlem Rocket Tours generally increase the value of communities that live on the waterfront by 8 to 10 percent."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Even with the proposed economic benefits, some West Harlem residents, like Joy Gramolini, worry about the high speed of the rocket tours."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“I have no problem with an ordinary tiny boat tour, that’s fine,” Gramolini said. “But something else that’s going fast and shooting up that river, I’m not so sure about that.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Trenk noted, however, that the tours would only operate at limited times of the day."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“The Rocket would be a certain amount of hours…” Trenk said. “We’re not really creating this nighttime [scene].”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Lonnie Portis, an environmental policy and advocacy coordinator at WE ACT for Environmental Justice, notes that while noise pollution could be a concern, the new tours mostly commercialize a space that is currently public."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“It’s like owning privatized access to waterfront, and we think that the community should have access to that,” Portis said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Johnson also noted that the new tours will be made financially accessible to the community through different discounts."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“The pricing is similar to some of the tours that are downtown,” Johnson said. “The difference is that we’re offering senior discounts, we’re offering children discounts, we’re offering discounts to people who live in a certain community.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "<i>Isha Banerjee and Erica Lee contributed reporting. </i>"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "<i>Deputy City News Editor Manuela Silva can be contacted at </i><i>manuela.silva@columbiaspectator.com</i><i>. Follow her on twitter at </i><a href=\"https://twitter.com/manuelas957\"><i>@manuelas957</i></a><i>.</i>"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "<b><i>Want to keep up with breaking news? Subscribe to our </i></b><a href=\"https://columbiaspectator.us4.list-manage.com/subscribe?u=a3d2eeb1ae5560ca04f82f042&id=e51c51d62d\"><b><i>email newsletter </i></b></a><b><i>and like Spectator on </i></b><a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/columbiaspectator\"><b><i>Facebook</i></b></a><b><i>. </i></b>"
            }
          ],
          "page_1": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The 135th Street Marine Transfer Station on the Hudson River has been unused since its closure in 1999. Now, Paradise Express Ferry, the company bringing the Harlem Rocket boat tours to the 125th Street piers this summer, imagines renovating the run-down facility into a new Harlem Maritime Technology Center and Museum."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Garry Johnson, founder and CEO of Paradise Express Ferry, presented this proposal at the Feb. 1 Community Board 9 landmarks, preservation, and parks meeting. The vision was first revealed in a Jan. 24 Patch article, which sparked online discussion and controversy regarding the potential new attractions."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Opened in 1955, the 28,000 square foot 135th Street Marine Transfer Station of the New York City Department of Sanitation was used to process over 1,000 tons of the city’s residential and commercial garbage per day."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“The 135th Street Transfer Station was closed in 1999 as part of the planned closure of the Fresh Kills Landfill,” DSNY press secretary Vincent Gragnani wrote in a statement to Spectator. “It was not reactivated as part of the 2006 Solid Waste Management Plan. The structure, which is more than five decades old, is in poor condition, and any future use would require substantial rehabilitation or full-scale replacement. While we currently do not have redevelopment plans, we appreciate the input of community stakeholders regarding the future of this facility.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The 24-hour waste center directly polluted the West Harlem area with exhaust, noise, and odors. Lonnie Portis, an environmental policy and advocacy coordinator at WE ACT for Environmental Justice, described the harmful, racially and socially inequitable health and environment effects of the 135th Street Marine Transfer Station on the West Harlem community, which aggravated the negative effects of the local bus depot and the North River Wastewater Treatment Plant."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“[It] exposed the community to … the odors, the constant noise in that area,” Portis said. “It was like a dumping ground for all sorts of hazardous waste and abandoned debris, and residents were exposed to even further harmful toxic substances and conditions.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "After the 135th Street MTS’s 1999 closure, the adjacent Hudson River waterfront from 125th Street to 135th Street was developed and opened in 2009 as the West Harlem Piers Park—yet the dilapidated 135th Street MTS remains unused."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“It’s a maritime structure,” Johnson said of the 135th Street MTS. “So why not convert it into a maritime museum?”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "In his presentation to CB9 earlier this month, Johnson explained that Paradise Express Ferry hopes to gain city and state approval to transform the 135th Street MTS into the first national maritime museum to showcase the maritime contributions of people of color."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“There’s a whole host of history that our community is just not aware of,” Johnson said. “People in the maritime world are [aware] to some extent, but it’s never been documented in one place. And that’s what we think: a rich history deserves to be on the waterfront in the nation’s most historic and internationally known African American community.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "West Harlem Piers Park goer Cassandra Robinson had never heard of Harlem’s maritime history, but she said, “We need to get the word out more.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Between 1903 and 1941, 125th Street had a working waterfront with a ferry terminal which shuttled passengers between Harlem and New Jersey. Johnson believes that the museum could also highlight the stories of historic Black maritime figures, such as Crispus Attucks, a sailor who was the first casualty in the Revolutionary War; Doris Miller, a Navy sailor who shot at Japanese planes at Pearl Harbor; and Matthew Henson, the first person of color to reach the North Pole."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Brian Wilson, another park enjoyer, had also never heard of Harlem's maritime past, saying, “I didn’t know nothing about that.” Still, he thought, “That museum would be good.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Over the past 20 years, numerous other proposals for the use of the 135th Street MTS have been made, including an aquaculture farm, hydroponics and mulching center, sailing school, and trade show and exhibition space for local artists and vendors. Portis from WEACT does not oppose the concept of a museum in the 135th Street MTS, but thinks that previous proposals for the renovation of the 135th Street MTS should still be considered."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“The community has already gotten together and already decided and had the vision already,” Portis said. “For [the 135th Street MTS], why not explore these visions before we look into these other options as well?”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Paradise Express Ferry projected that the museum would attract 60,000 visitors per year."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Cassandra Robinson also highlighted that in addition to providing more attractions, the projects would also increase local revenue and create more jobs for nearby residents."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“We’ve got hard working people right here,” Robinson said. “And they need good jobs.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "In addition to the economic benefits, the museum’s pier could also act as a rest office for US Coast Guard or NYPD Harbor Police and an emergency maritime command center for the NYC/USCG during natural disasters."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The museum would also host maritime training facilities, opening up new career opportunities to people in New York City, especially those in offshore wind, which Johnson calls an up-and-coming industry."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Part of the reason for building out this museum is it also becomes a workforce development training site to get people of color into the maritime community and into offshore wind which is the next big industry,” Johnson said. “We need to train this community so that they can participate in this industry that is just beginning, but is 20 years into maturity in Europe. In Europe, there are 20,000 offshore wind turbines. In the United States there are seven.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Paradise Express Ferry hopes to open the doors of the Harlem Maritime Technology Center and Museum in 2027 or 2028. Right now, however, Johnson stresses that the plans for the Museum are still in its early conceptual stages."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“The museum and the [ferris] wheel are proposed concepts. We don’t have permission for that. There hasn't been a process that we've gone through with the city to acquire this structure or to build that pier or whatever the case may be,” Johnson said. “But why not?”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "<i>Isha Banerjee and Manuela Silva contributed reporting. </i>"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "<i>Staff writer Erica Lee can be contacted at </i><i>erica.lee@columbiaspectator.com</i><i>. Follow Spectator on twitter at </i><a href=\"https://twitter.com/manuelas957\"><i>@</i></a><i>columbiaspec</i><i>.</i>"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "<b><i>Want to keep up with breaking news? Subscribe to our </i></b><a href=\"https://columbiaspectator.us4.list-manage.com/subscribe?u=a3d2eeb1ae5560ca04f82f042&id=e51c51d62d\"><b><i>email newsletter </i></b></a><b><i>and like Spectator on </i></b><a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/columbiaspectator\"><b><i>Facebook</i></b></a><b><i>. </i></b>"
            }
          ],
          "page_2": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "A patch of green space, a pristine waterfront, and a bustling community characterize the 125th Street Piers in West Harlem. Earlier this month, however, Paradise Express Ferry announced their vision to change the park with three new attractions, including a museum about Harlem’s maritime history, a zipping rocket boat tour, and a ferris wheel. While some members of the community are excited for a new attraction in the neighborhood, others worry about its environmental and commercial implications for the park."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The rocket boat tour is the only confirmed attraction set to open in the summer of 2023, while the ferris wheel and the museum are still in their conceptual planning stages. Of these three new attractions, the most visible one will be the new 180-foot tall ferris wheel which, pending approval, is hoped to open in the summer of 2024."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The Harlem Wheel, the first wheel set to be built in the heart of New York City, is said to have “spectacular” views of the Hudson River and the Harlem neighborhood, according to Paradise Express Ferry, the group spearheading the project. The wheel will be visible from New Jersey, the George Washington Bridge, and the Upper West Side."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“The wheel just becomes an iconic presence,” Garry Anderson Johnson, CEO of Paradise Express Ferry, said. “It becomes the beacon that attracts people to that waterfront, where they can experience not only the views from the wheel, but the history and the culture of the museum.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Paradise Express Ferry predicts that the wheel, with 21 gondolas for eight adults each, will bring in 225,000 people annually, upon opening."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“I'm all for [the ferris wheel],” Cassandra Robinson, a West Harlem resident, said. “Yeah, I'm all for it because we need a little bit more attraction,”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The West Harlem Piers Park was developed by WE ACT, an environmental justice advocacy group, to engage the community with a peaceful green space for all members of the community to access. Despite growing support for the ferris wheel from local residents, some members of the environmental justice group are wary of whether there is a need for a communal waterfront to be a tourist attraction."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“It's a community park,” Lonnie Portis, an environmental policy and advocacy coordinator at WE ACT, said. “It's who live here, who work here, who worship here, and play here, it is for the community. It's not necessarily for tourists, and tourists are definitely obviously welcome to enjoy the park as is, but there doesn't need to be an attraction there.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "WE ACT has played a large part in establishing 125th Street Piers of West Harlem. In 1998, WE ACT, in partnership with Community Board 9, created the Harlem on the River project with the goal of increasing waterfront access for the local community. After working with more than 200 residents, the New York City Department of Parks and Recreation, and the Economic Development Corporation, the park finally opened in 2009."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The park was created in response to a “decades-long environmental injustice issue” in West Harlem. For former Parks Commissioner Adrian Benape, the introduction of a ferris wheel could contradict that purpose of the park."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Finally, the city [is] spending lots of money, an excess of $20 million, to build a very small waterfront park in this former desolate pier structure,” Benape said. “It's a beautiful little park; it really serves the community in a very nice way.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Portis echoed Benape’s sentiments, saying that Paradise Express Ferry is acting against the wants of the community."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“The community is basically being sacrificed solely for commercial benefit for like a handful of individuals,” Portis said. “If Harlem wanted a neighborhood park or ferris wheel or something like that, then that's what they would have come up with when we had our community visioning plan, but they didn't. They wanted parking access to green space, and they wanted everyone to be able to enjoy it. So therefore, we're firmly opposed to the construction of the ferris wheel.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "However, some local business owners believe that introducing a ferris wheel, led by a Harlem-based business, into West Harlem Piers Park will incentivize members of the community to spend their money at local businesses."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“It creates reasons for people to spend money in the communities or in the area. It just helps local businesses,” Michael Trenk, owner of the Baylander Steel Beach restaurant which is docked on the West Harlem Pier, said. “I'd be totally in favor. The more people that can be exposed to that park, the more people that can wander by the Baylander, the more people might want a drink or something to eat after they go on this ferris wheel.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Other residents said they support the construction of the ferris wheel because it does not bring many disturbances and also makes the park more “fun.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“[The ferris wheel] doesn’t make a lot of noise,” Joy Gramolini, a West Harlem resident, said. “It'll be fun. It's not going to be lighting up somebody's living room or something like that.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "As the projects are proposed, members of the community believe that there needs to be a more thorough consideration into the impacts of the weather on the ferris wheel, its safety, how the city will manage the extra parking space, and how the community will respond to more police presence in the area due to higher tourism."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Johnson and his team have proposed to use electricity purchased from renewable sources to generate the energy for the ferris wheel. However, they are still waiting for approval from environmental reviews."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“As far as the wheel is concerned, depending on approvals and environmental reviews and passage of that, we would love to see the city build another pier that would support the wheel and then on this pier would be charging stations for vessels,” Johnson said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "For Benape, the expansion of the park will not only take away from the purpose of the park, but will also do little to boost tourism in the area."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“The whole idea is if you want to build tourism in West Harlem, the ferris wheel is not the way to do it because you're destroying a neighborhood,” Benape said. “But there's a sort of very deeply mistaken notion, really a perverse notion, that parks are empty spaces upon which to deposit your commercial dreams. That’s just not the case.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Portis also raised his concerns about the potential environmental costs of building the ferris wheel in the park."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“[The environmental impact of building the ferris wheel] is obviously taking away a green place to access the waterfront and then again, you have to have the parking lot, concepts that need to be there as well,” Portis said. “So you're kind of adding those kinds of negative, I guess, externalities by building this.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "<i>Manuela Silva and Erica Lee contributed reporting.</i>"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "<i>Staff Writer Isha Banerjee can be contacted at </i><a href=\"mailto:Isha.Banerjee@columbiaspectator.com\"><i>Isha.Banerjee@columbiaspectator.com</i></a><i>. Follow her on Twitter </i><a href=\"https://twitter.com/ishabanerjee20\"><i>@ishabanerjee.20</i></a><i>.</i>"
            },
